metadata.name: Unfinished Loom #114
metadata.description:
The 'Unfinished Loom' is a generative system that produces variations of itself through rotations, displacements, and self-repetition. 

Self-similarity in the loom is achieved by repeating the double grid system and its elements vertically (using the 'o' and 'l' keys) and horizontally (using the 'i' and 'k' keys).

Pressing 'a' produces automatic changes, while pressing 'x' reverts to the original composition.

By clicking on the canvas, you can play with colors and transparency. 

The '1' key toggles between disorder and order. 
The '2' and '3' keys allow you to toggle displacements.
The '4' key enables you to switch between entropy or not.
The '5' key lets you switch between mixed textures or assigned textures. 

You can reduce, amplify, or flip the displacement using the 'u' or 'j' key. 
To remove a color press 'c'. To reset to all colors, press 'v'.

You can save a PNG file using 's', a JPG using 'd', a PNG with twice your window height using 'f', and a print size image using 'g'.

This work explores composition based on generative double grid system, where rotations, displacements and noisy lines intertwine to form a playful loom.

Created with p5.js rendering in WEBGL.

metadata.name: BLOCK PARTY #13
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm exploring isometric grids and recursive divisions with an emphasis on contrasting colors.

A random rectange division is so simple yet creates vastly different and interesting outputs.

An isometric grid provides a unique perspective to the recursion giving each piece a certain depth and contrast.

When does chaotic randomness become beauty and what interesting patterns may emerge?

Press 's' in live mode to save image. Best viewed after save.

* Original code by Matt Lehoullier with p5.js

The Morixels Monkey is a Random Generated 128 PFP NFT.
This collection is manually designed.
The original Artwork was designed in 25 by 25 pixels and then resized to 2000 by 2000 resolution.
The number of Traits in this collection is 10 (134 layers) and it has the ability to make 31,500,000,000 different Monkeys.

Some ​layers are less than 1 percent of the total, some 100 percent, and some between 0.1 and 100 percent.

To create balance, these NFTs are randomly minted, and this is a chance for everyone to get a rare version. So due to the low price of these NFTs, if the rare version did not belong to you, it is still possible for you to mint the new NFTs.
To Produce this collection, all the layers were designed pixel by pixel, which was time-consuming and difficult. And this greatly increases the value of this collection.

Because this is an NFT in PFP format, you can put it on your avatar on Twitter or Instagram.

Twitter: @Morixels

Website: https://morixels.com/

metadata.name: Transition: Multidimensional #88
metadata.description:
The world is always and has always been in constant transition. Transitions have created and destroyed everything. Understanding and living with transitions is fundamental to being in the universe.

Transition is not one-dimensional. It is not just a move from A to B, but rather a constant shifting between A to F to % to 9 to AA to €. It is multi-faceted and multi-dimensional. This implies that binaries are merely imagined.

With this piece, I explore the idea of transitions being multidimensional by using shapes which progressively increase in edge count in all manner of ways. 

You’ll witness transitions that happen slowly, quickly, in fits and starts, and chaotically.

You’ll find transitions placed in circles, grids, towers, spirals, and more.

You’ll see transitions in multiple color schemes including inverted versions of each scheme. 

Interactions

A - Start/stop cumulative animation

B - Start/stop independent animation

S - Save image

metadata.name: Wings #4
metadata.description:
Alexander Calder once said, “Well, the archaeologist will tell you there's a little bit of Miró in Calder and a little bit of Calder in Miró.” I feel there is a little of both Miró and Calder in these fanciful pieces. I have called the project, Wings, because I feel get it off the ground. The breakthrough came when I suddenly realized that instead of thinking in terms of lines, I needed to think a sense of flight as I look at them. And flight was the sensation I felt when the pieces of the project finally fell into place. While I have done several generative image compositions, this is my first piece of art to be fully algorithmic, and I struggled to in terms of parabolas.

The background color for each piece is randomly chosen, while the shapes are always black and the lines always white. As I developed the code, I experimented with several different approaches to color, but I kept coming back to this simple palette. It seemed to me to emphasize motion without distraction.

The drawing grid is divided randomly into 10 to 100 divisions. Each crosshair on the grid becomes a starting point for a mark, with these starting points chosen randomly as the code repeats a number of drawing loops. With these four random inputs - grid division, color, coordinate, and number of loops - the unique possibilities number in the hundreds of millions. A few are offered for your enjoyment here.

I’d like to give a shout out to those who helped me in my fx(hash) learning curve. Thank you josemiguel.tez and Elout de Kok. I also leaned heavily and with gratitude on Rune Madson’s, Programming Design Systems (https://programmingdesignsystems.com), and on the supportive folks in the community Discord.

Created by Wanda Oliver (wandaoliver.tez) in Sept., 2022.
This work is licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

Press [S] in live mode to save with high-resolution.

metadata.name: Charcoal Brutalism #143
metadata.description:
Based on a similar technique as "Charcoal Landscapes", using lines limited to 8 possible directions, this work is about the repetition of patterns at different scales and the use of negative spaces.
The texture created from the noise combined with the structures that emerges from this algorithm create a look similar to the brutalist architecture of the last century.

There are 10 scale variations but with almost infinite possible outcomes.
Inverted colours have a small chance of dropping.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: ‘Low-Res’ poems #25
metadata.description:
‘Low-Res’ poems is a collection as a high-tech alternative search. It was made with two free small, lightweight softwares like kidpix.app and magicavoxel, using the @PureSpider template to create iterations. This collection  is produced from technological limitations, a socioeconomic condition implies a determined political position and this is reflected on the access to technology, mainly the access to hardware.
As an artist, not having access to specialized high-tech hardware and software made my workflow, or the way I approach art, different, putting me in a place where I had to open myself and embrace low-poly or low-res alternatives to continue making art.

‘Low-Res’ has 50 MagicaVoxel models in 3D and 6 backgrounds made in kidpix.app, in each piece, the features combinations build corny poems, which give each piece an unique spirit and name. These poems work as a continuation of the Digital Collage collection.

High res tech has often been a vector of cultural hegemony over the global south, especially in terms of access to the tech- Sabatobox @sabatobox

metadata.name: Color Study I #3
metadata.description:
Color Study I, my second algorithmic project, is based in an exploration of generative color systems. I wanted to create an approach to generative color that was systemized, entirely randomized, and packaged in such a way as to be repeatable for any project.  Furthermore, I wanted to support a full range of hues, analogous colors, complementary colors, tints, shades, and tones.  And ultimately, I wanted consistently harmonious results.  A model that produced combinations that made me recoil on sight was unacceptable.

The model I created for the project is based on tetradic complements using the HSB color mode. An array of tetrads encompassing the entire color wheel is initially set up.  In each iterative generation, a primary hue is randomly selected and forms the basis of a working tetrad. With a design comprised of four major elements, random hue-element associations are then established.  Finally, saturation and brightness values are randomly selected, within a set of given constraints, for each major element. Swatches are added to incorporate white, black, and the fully saturated, brightest hues of the tetrad.

Created by Wanda Oliver (wandaoliver.tez) in Sept., 2022.
This work is licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

Press [S] in live mode to save with high-resolution.

metadata.name: inlim:in #228
metadata.description:
"inlim:in" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

Atemporal iridescent fragments of the in between. The series is inspired by the many liminal spaces and unseen influences that permeate the visible universe and its participants. Created with GLSL, every piece of the series is generated using the space around the visible object to cast its shape. The series creates a gentle and colorful expanse through which viewers might contemplate what it is to exist at an infinite threshold.

metadata.name: Anachronous #218
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022
